</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The Darkening</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Heh, Ash we've always known you have the eye of every MMORPG on you. I'm sure Mickey Soft and Turbine is quaking in their boots at the thought that you might migrate to their game next, and bring your team of Programmers with you.<p>*Envisions Ashran's team as the 4 Horsemen, despite there being more or less than 4*<p><br>I think you should Migrate to AC when it finishes or UO2 at least...<p>Only time will tell, no?
</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kal</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kai,<p>Don't you think it would be easier to start with something like CrystalSpace and develop from there?<p>I think the 3D technology in EQ is a little out of date.  With the features of other publicly available engines, why take so much longer to reverse engineer when you can just take an existing codebase and build on it?<p>I would love to work on a MMORPG project where I can give creative input.  I am not a programming god either, but I can read and modify similar to what Kai stated his skills were.<p>But, why develop an emulator when your client uses a 3-year-old 3D engine?<p>How about reverse engineering a CLIENT instead.. and add graphics features and automation? That would kick some ass.<br>It would also enable a hell of a lot of cheating with a few scripting features.<br>Imagine coding something like this in an EQ scripting language:<p>while (1) {<br>  if (encumbered()) {<br>    sell(); // triggers a routine that<br>  // walks to a shop (hardcoded loc) and<br>  // sells items that are "non essential"<br>  // (hardcoded list.. rusty, FS, etc)<br>  }<br>  else if (totalmana/currentmana &lt; 40) {<br>    meditate(2); // med for 2 minutes<p>  else if (totalhealth/currenthealth &lt; 40) {<br>    cast(greater_heal);<br>  }<br>  else if (<br>    seek_and_destroy(lvl-3,lvl-1);<br>  // routine to pick a random mob of lower<br>  // level in the zone (hardcode bad choices,<br>  // to preserve faction etc),<br>  // pick a path with random wandering thrown<br>  // in to prevent detection by Verant,<br>  // kill it, and loot.  Would be a <br>  // complicated routine, but doable.<br>  }<br>}<p>You could leave this on all night while you're sleeping, gain 3 levels, and get tons of loot.  Sure, there's a lot of caveats as far as you would have to be in a relatively safe, flat zone, etc.  You could use it to forage thousands of pieces of food, make thousands in plat by killing greens, etc.<p>Now, with that said, I think cheating to get ahead in the game would be boring and unethical.  Why play?  To me, I would program something like this just to have fun, and not use it on a regular basis.<br>I would write a bot to go to a newbie area and go around casting heals on anyone under 50% health, cast SOW, and say things like "I hate rain!" and "No one expects the Spanish Inquisition!"<p>I'm not advocating something like this, I just think it might be easier than a server emulator.<p>Kai, if you need an 'idea man' for your programming projects, let me know.  I have extensive gaming experience, and have done a lot of designing for my own projects.<p>Kal<br>unix_guy@hotmail.com<br>
</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Koregin</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sorry, not to sound strange or mean or anything... but after reading that last post I was confused. What language did you learn to program in? I mean it seems to resemble the C++(maybe BASIC) that I learned, but I never learned coded commands called sell(), or IF Encumbered() or any of those things.... oh well, guess maybe I need to go and hit the books again, must have missed something.
</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The Darkening</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Heh, if you didn't get it Kai was just tossing examples out of his BO (Back Orifice). Simply enough he's saying you could create functions such as those (program specific functions mind you) to allow it easier. Much like MUD/MUSH servers have MUD/MUSH specific coding with functions that do not exist elsewhere unless they shared the code.
</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Acid</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">This whole server emu thing is startin to piss me off.  I could make a server emu in about a month.  after all im only emulating a program, not a system like N64 or something. Only thing is, I have yet to find a decent packet sniffer that will work with EQ. Almost all of the packet sniffers out there are ethernet only and wont work over a dial up TCP/IP stack.  If anyone has a packet sniffer that works with eq, let me know.
